      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Keep the Mideast Talks Alive</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Irving Sager letter suggests that next US president ask Bill Clinton to continue as mediator in Mideast peace efforts</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A U.S. Role Is Crucial for Peace,'' by Chas. W. Freeman Jr. (Op-Ed, Oct. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A U.S. Role Is Crucial for Peace,'' by Chas. W. Freeman Jr. (Op-Ed, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>Mr. Freeman says President Clinton ''cannot restart the peace process, and his successor, whoever he is, will have to rebuild trust with both sides.'' Yet if George W. Bush and Al Gore jointly requested Mr. Clinton to continue as mediator in the next administration, regardless of who is elected, the prospects for the negotiations would be greatly increased.</p>
        <p>Thus, Mr. Clinton would be able to continue to function as mediator without being hampered by the impending end of his administration, and the parties would understand that America is united in seeking a fair and peaceful outcome.</p>
        <p>IRVING SAGER  New York, Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
